<dl id="n15030a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n15" href="#n15030a">N15 (VI.D.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n15all.htm#n15030a"> 30(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> pens at work</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The example set by Ari did not long remain unfruitful. During the second half of the twelfth century there must have been much literary activity in Iceland, and many <mark>pens must have been at work</mark> recording local and foreign history, whether handed down from earlier times by tradition, or learned by special inquiry from still living authorities. <small> W. A. Craige, <a name="ICEL" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ICEL"><cite title="source">The Icelandic Sagas</cite></a>, (1913) 25-6</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c15206a" href="c15all.htm#c15206a">VI.C.15:206(a)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
